INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '1d340a12-5caa-4bf1-8439-ecb0533f2bbe',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Azure Container Apps vs AKS — When PaaS DX Beats IaaS Control$escape$,
  $escape$Azure spans the full spectrum from Railway-style push-and-go to raw infrastructure ownership. Azure Container Apps is Azure's direct competitor to Fly.io and Railway — deploy a container image from ACR, get HTTPS termination, Dapr integration, KEDA-powered autoscaling, and scale-to-zero on the consumption plan with zero Kubernetes YAML. Azure App Service plays the Vercel role for web workloads: deployment slots, custom domains, managed TLS, and Linux/Windows runtime stacks in under five minutes.

The ceiling appears fast. Container Apps locks you into Envoy as the ingress proxy; you can't swap CNI plugins or configure node-level sysctls. VNet integration requires the Workload Profiles plan, not the default consumption tier. Cold starts on scale-from-zero can hit 2–4 seconds under bursty traffic.

AKS is the IaaS escape hatch. You control node pool SKUs, cluster autoscaler profiles, custom NSG rules, and the full Kubernetes API surface — including GPU workloads, PodDisruptionBudgets, and Calico network policies. The cost: you own upgrade windows, node image patches, and ingress controller configuration.

Default to Container Apps. Escalate to AKS when VNet segmentation, GPU node pools, or fine-grained pod scheduling become non-negotiable.$escape$,
  $escape$# PaaS: Azure Container Apps — production-ready in one command
az containerapp create \
  --name my-api \
  --resource-group rg-prod \
  --environment my-env \
  --image myacr.azurecr.io/api:latest \
  --target-port 8080 \
  --ingress external \
  --min-replicas 0 --max-replicas 10

# IaaS: AKS — cluster is just the start
az aks create --name my-cluster --resource-group rg-prod \
  --node-count 3 --node-vm-size Standard_D4s_v3 \
  --network-plugin azure --enable-addons monitoring
# Still need: kubectl apply for ingress, cert-manager, HPA, PDB, Dapr...$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
